LLM Notebooks — README
This repository contains "5"(2026/3/26, keep update) hands-on notebooks for exploring Large Language Models (LLMs). These tools range from fundamental architecture to practical writing assistants and hardware optimization guides.

1. model_weights_tokens_polished.ipynb
Model Weights and Tokens: Numbers All the Way Down

Based on the original framework by Instructor Eric, adapted for improved readability and accessibility.

Key Features:

New Interactive Elements: Added UI components to visualize how text is broken into tokens in real-time.

Beginner-Friendly Tour: Explains how GGUF files store metadata and weights.

Visualizing Meaning: Explores embeddings and high-dimensional clustering (PCA).

Model: qwen2-1_5b-instruct-q4_0.gguf

2. QwenTestTaker-shared.ipynb
Qwen SAT Test Taker

Originally developed by Sanjana; updated and optimized for performance and usability.

Key Enhancements:

Stability & Flow: Optimized the execution logic to ensure a smoother run in Jupyter environments.

Structured Output: Refactored open-ended AI responses into a indexed answer format.

Readable JSON: Modified the output logic to transform raw model responses into a clean, human-readable format.

Model: qwen2-1_5b-instruct-q4_0.gguf

3. Personal_Writing_Assistant.ipynb
Personal Writing Assistant (v4.0)

Author: SzuLun Huang, UC Berkeley Data Science.

Latest Update (2026/03/26):

Accessibility Fix: Transitioned to a light-theme background to ensure text-to-background contrast meets the 4:1 accessibility requirement.

Display Optimization: Fixed internal Jupyter rendering errors to ensure UI elements (sliders and tables) display correctly across different browsers.

Focus: A deep dive into prompt engineering, few-shot learning, and AI parameter control (temperature, frequency penalty).

4. LLM_Explorer_Jupyter_0306.ipynb
LLM Explorer — The 4GB VRAM Decision Guide

Focus: A data-driven guide to choosing the right AI model based on your hardware.

Features:

Fetches live data from HuggingFace to calculate real VRAM requirements.

Compares quantization formats (FP16 vs Q4_K_M) against benchmark scores.

5. hello_agent.ipynb
Hello Agent — Build Your Own AI Agent from Scratch
Author: [Your Name], UC Berkeley Data Science.

A hands-on introduction to AI agents — from zero to a working agent in one session.

Key Features:
- Agent Loop: Implements a full ReAct-style agent loop (decide → act → observe → repeat) using llama.cpp locally.
- Tools: Four tools with safety restrictions — web search (DuckDuckGo), read/write files (locked to workspace), and shell execution (Human-in-the-Loop approval).
- Robust JSON Parsing: Handles messy model output with a three-strategy fallback parser.
- Interactive UI: Widget-based interface to run the agent on any task and inspect the full agent trace.
- Robot Quiz: Hangman-style quiz to test understanding of agent concepts.

Model: Llama-3.2-1B-Instruct-Q4_K_M.gguf
